1
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:07,000
Your event is set up.

2
00:00:07,300 --> 00:00:09,300
Sessions are in.

3
00:00:09,600 --> 00:00:11,600
It's showtime.

4
00:00:11,900 --> 00:00:15,650
In this episode I'm going to walk you through the

5
00:00:15,950 --> 00:00:18,200
entire session lifecycle — from PLANNED,

6
00:00:18,500 --> 00:00:21,125
through READY, CALLING, LIVE, HOLD, and ENDED.

7
00:00:21,425 --> 00:00:23,675
This is the core of CueDeck,

8
00:00:23,975 --> 00:00:27,350
and once you understand how the state machine works,

9
00:00:27,650 --> 00:00:29,900
running a complex event becomes straightforward.

10
00:00:30,200 --> 00:00:33,950
Every session in CueDeck lives in one of eight states:

11
00:00:34,250 --> 00:00:36,500
PLANNED — it's on the programme,

12
00:00:36,800 --> 00:00:38,800
nothing has happened yet.

13
00:00:39,100 --> 00:00:41,725
READY — the room is set up,

14
00:00:42,025 --> 00:00:44,025
we're expecting the speaker.

15
00:00:44,325 --> 00:00:47,700
CALLING — the speaker is being called to stage.

16
00:00:47,1000 --> 00:00:50,250
LIVE — on stage right now.

17
00:00:50,550 --> 00:00:53,550
HOLD — live but paused, speaker is waiting.

18
00:00:53,850 --> 00:00:57,600
OVERRUN — the session went past its scheduled end time.

19
00:00:57,900 --> 00:00:59,900
ENDED — finished.

20
00:01:00,200 --> 00:01:02,825
CANCELLED — removed from the running order.

21
00:01:03,125 --> 00:01:05,125
Transitions flow in one direction.

22
00:01:05,425 --> 00:01:09,175
You can't accidentally move a session backwards through the machine.

23
00:01:09,475 --> 00:01:12,475
And every state change is timestamped and logged.

24
00:01:12,775 --> 00:01:15,775
It's 9:15 — fifteen minutes before the keynote.

25
00:01:16,075 --> 00:01:18,075
The room is set up.

26
00:01:18,375 --> 00:01:20,625
Let's move Sarah's session to READY.

27
00:01:20,925 --> 00:01:23,175
Click the session to select it.

28
00:01:23,475 --> 00:01:25,725
The context panel shows 'Set Ready'.

29
00:01:26,025 --> 00:01:28,025
Click it.

30
00:01:28,325 --> 00:01:31,325
The card flips to a green READY badge.

31
00:01:31,625 --> 00:01:34,625
Every connected device — the stage manager's phone,

32
00:01:34,925 --> 00:01:37,550
the AV laptop, the display monitors —

33
00:01:37,850 --> 00:01:39,850
updates in under a second.

34
00:01:40,150 --> 00:01:42,150
9:25.

35
00:01:42,450 --> 00:01:44,700
Time to call Sarah to stage.

36
00:01:44,1000 --> 00:01:46,1000
Click CALLING.

37
00:01:47,300 --> 00:01:51,050
The card goes amber — every stage manager knows to

38
00:01:51,350 --> 00:01:53,350
go find the speaker.

39
00:01:53,650 --> 00:01:57,400
The broadcast bar can send a message to the whole

40
00:01:57,700 --> 00:01:59,950
crew at the same time —

41
00:02:00,250 --> 00:02:02,500
we'll cover that in episode five.

42
00:02:02,800 --> 00:02:04,800
Sarah's on stage.

43
00:02:05,100 --> 00:02:07,100
It's 9:30.

44
00:02:07,400 --> 00:02:09,400
Hit GO LIVE.

45
00:02:09,700 --> 00:02:11,950
The session card turns bright green,

46
00:02:12,250 --> 00:02:14,500
the status changes to LIVE, and

47
00:02:14,800 --> 00:02:16,800
the actual_start timestamp is recorded.

48
00:02:17,100 --> 00:02:19,100
The clock starts.

49
00:02:19,400 --> 00:02:21,650
If you have digital displays or

50
00:02:21,950 --> 00:02:24,575
a stage confidence monitor set up —

51
00:02:24,875 --> 00:02:27,500
we'll build those in episodes eight and

52
00:02:27,800 --> 00:02:31,550
nine — they all flip to show this session live.

53
00:02:31,850 --> 00:02:34,100
Sometimes you need to pause mid-session.

54
00:02:34,400 --> 00:02:37,025
Fire alarm, technical issue, speaker needs water.

55
00:02:37,325 --> 00:02:39,325
Hit HOLD.

56
00:02:39,625 --> 00:02:41,625
The session freezes.

57
00:02:41,925 --> 00:02:43,925
The stage timer freezes.

58
00:02:44,225 --> 00:02:47,225
Everyone on every device sees the HOLD state.

59
00:02:47,525 --> 00:02:50,900
When you're ready to resume, click LIVE again —

60
00:02:51,200 --> 00:02:53,825
the session continues from where it was,

61
00:02:54,125 --> 00:02:56,125
timer picks back up.

62
00:02:56,425 --> 00:02:59,425
Sarah went 3 minutes over on her demo.

63
00:02:59,725 --> 00:03:03,100
We need to adjust the rest of the programme.

64
00:03:03,400 --> 00:03:07,150
The nudge buttons add or subtract a minute from the

65
00:03:07,450 --> 00:03:09,450
current session's end time.

66
00:03:09,750 --> 00:03:13,500
The delay cascade automatically shifts every subsequent PLANNED session forward.

67
00:03:13,800 --> 00:03:18,675
You can see the knock-on effect ripple down the session list in realtime.

68
00:03:18,975 --> 00:03:22,350
We'll go deep on delay management in episode six.

69
00:03:22,650 --> 00:03:24,650
Session done.

70
00:03:24,950 --> 00:03:26,950
Click END SESSION.

71
00:03:27,250 --> 00:03:30,250
Status flips to ENDED with a green check.

72
00:03:30,550 --> 00:03:32,550
Actual end time is recorded.

73
00:03:32,850 --> 00:03:35,850
The time variance — how far over or

74
00:03:36,150 --> 00:03:38,775
under planned — is calculated and stored.

75
00:03:39,075 --> 00:03:42,450
You'll see all of this in the post-event report.

76
00:03:42,750 --> 00:03:45,750
On the next session — the panel —

77
00:03:46,050 --> 00:03:50,550
you can mark speakers as arrived before the session is even called.

78
00:03:50,850 --> 00:03:54,600
The stage manager ticks 'Speaker Arrived' on each panellist as

79
00:03:54,900 --> 00:03:56,900
they check in backstage.

80
00:03:57,200 --> 00:04:01,325
Directors can see at a glance whether all speakers are present.

81
00:04:01,625 --> 00:04:05,000
This feeds into the pre-cue AI agent too —

82
00:04:05,300 --> 00:04:07,300
but that's episode ten.

83
00:04:07,600 --> 00:04:09,600
That's the full session lifecycle.

84
00:04:09,900 --> 00:04:13,275
PLANNED → READY → CALLING → LIVE → ENDED,

85
00:04:13,575 --> 00:04:16,575
with HOLD and delay nudges along the way.

86
00:04:16,875 --> 00:04:20,250
In the next episode we'll look at roles —

87
00:04:20,550 --> 00:04:22,800
how to invite your team and

88
00:04:23,100 --> 00:04:25,725
what each role can see and do.

89
00:04:26,025 --> 00:04:28,025
See you in episode four.
